    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-cbp-experimental-campaign-test-split"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/cpb-ml-nominal-test-set-performance",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Nominal test-set RH prediction accuracy",
      "description": "The gradient-boosted ensemble surrogate was evaluated on 120 held-out samples drawn from the same experimental campaign distribution as the 480-sample training set (80/20 stratified split by flow-speed bin). Mean absolute error in RH was 0.031 (95% CI: 0.027–0.035) and R² = 0.974. All five nominal flow-speed operating points (4, 5, 6, 7, 8 L/min × 2400, 3000 RPM) were represented in both splits. The surrogate correctly ranked worst-case hemolysis conditions in 118 of 120 test cases."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/cpb-ml-single-ood-point",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Single out-of-distribution operating point evaluation",
      "description": "One additional operating condition (flow = 7 L/min, speed = 3200 RPM) outside the nominal training envelope was evaluated against a dedicated CFD run. The surrogate predicted RH = 0.87; the CFD reference yielded RH = 0.91, a 4.4% relative error. The assessment narrative states this result 'demonstrates that the model generalizes well beyond the training envelope.' No repeated OOD sampling, no systematic covariate-shift study, and no statistical confidence bounds on generalization error are provided. Noise injection and adversarial perturbation analyses are absent."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/cpb-ml-cross-validation-nominal",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "5-fold cross-validation on nominal campaign data",
      "description": "5-fold cross-validation was performed entirely within the experimental campaign dataset. Mean CV R² = 0.971 ± 0.008 across folds. Folds were stratified by flow-speed bin, preserving the same input-feature distribution across all folds. No fold contained samples from geometrically distinct pump variants or different blood analogue formulations. This result corroborates in-distribution predictive accuracy but provides no evidence of robustness to distribution shift."
    }
  ],
