      "rationale": "The gradient-boosted ensemble uses deterministic tree traversal with double-precision arithmetic. Prediction variance attributable to floating-point rounding is less than 1e-6 in RH units, negligible compared to model MAE of 0.031. No iterative solver is involved; this factor is interpreted as numerical stability of the ML inference pipeline."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Input validation guards prevent application of surrogate outside documented feature ranges; user documentation specifies COU scope.",
      "rationale": "The inference API enforces range checks on all five input features (flow rate, rotational speed, gap clearance, impeller diameter, blade angle) and raises a structured warning if inputs exceed training-data bounds by more than 5%. User documentation explicitly states the surrogate is validated for the five nominal COU operating points and should not be used for extrapolation without additional validation. The single OOD point evaluation (7 L/min, 3200 RPM) was conducted under controlled assessment conditions, not routine use."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form (gradient-boosted ensemble) is appropriate for the nonlinear hemolysis response surface; model selection is justified against alternatives.",
      "rationale": "Gradient-boosted ensemble was selected after comparison against linear regression, random forest, and a shallow neural network on a 20% holdout. The ensemble achieved the lowest MAE and best RH ranking accuracy. The hemolysis response surface is known to be nonlinear in tip speed and clearance gap, which tree-based methods capture without explicit feature engineering. Model form is appropriate for the nominal operating regime. Behavior under input distribution shift is not part of the model-form assessment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
